04636nam a22006495i 9780691187242DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182002nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911872427 a10.1515/97806911872422doi  a(DE-B1597)501750  a(OCoLC)1076408722  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aQC793.5.Q252bS65 2003eb 7aSCI0510002bisacsh04a539.7/21672231 aSmith, Timothy Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHidden Worlds :bHunting for Quarks in Ordinary Matter /cTimothy Paul Smith. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4c©2002  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Hidden Worlds: The Search for Quarks in Ordinary Matter -- t2. The Rise and Fall (for the Right Reasons) and Rise Again of the Quark Hypothesis -- t3. The Players and the Stage -- t4. The Nature of the Evidence -- t5. Measuring a Rainbow -- t6. Particle Taxonomy and Quark Soup -- t7. The Shape of Things -- t8. Three Quarks Plus -- t9. Digging a Little Deeper -- t10. A New Age of Exploration within the Hidden World -- tGlossary -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNo one has ever seen a quark. Yet physicists seem to know quite a lot about the properties and behavior of these ubiquitous elementary particles. Here a top researcher introduces us to a fascinating but invisible realm that is part of our everyday life. Timothy Smith tells us what we know about quarks--and how we know it. Though the quarks that make science headlines are typically laboratory creations generated under extreme conditions, most quarks occur naturally. They reside in the protons and neutrons that make up almost all of the universe's known matter, from human DNA to distant nebulae, from books and tables to neutron stars. Smith explains what these quarks are, how they act, and why physicists believe in them sight unseen. How do quarks arrange themselves? What other combinations can nature make? How do quarks hold nuclei together? What else is happening in their hidden worlds? It turns out that these questions can be answered using a few simple principles, such as the old standby: opposites attract. With these few principles, Smith shows how quarks dance around each other and explains what physicists mean when they refer to "up" and "down" quarks and talk about a quark's color, flavor, and spin. Smith also explains how we know what we know about these oddly aloof particles, which are eternally confined inside larger particles. He explains how quark experiments are mounted and how massive accelerators, targets, and detectors work together to collect the data that scientists use to infer what quarks are up to. A nonmathematical tour of the quark world, this book is written for students, educators, and all who enjoy scientific exploration--whether they seek a taste of subnuclear physics or just wonder about nature on the smallest of scales.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aQuarks. 7aSCIENCE / Physics / Nuclear.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187242zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691187242423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187242.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MTPY  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MTPY  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA